he network, previously known as the Indianapolis Motor Speedway Radio Network, had changed its name for 1998, to reflect its coverage of the entire Indy Racing League season. At least 541 affiliates carried the broadcast across the United States.<ref>1998 Indianapolis 500 - Daily Trackside Report; pg. 105</ref>\n\n[[Bob Jenkins]] served as chief announcer for the ninth and final year. It would be Jenkins 20th and final year on the radio network crew (until his brief return in 2007-2008). In addition, Jerry Baker celebrated his milestone 25th year on the broadcast.\n\n[[Johnny Rutherford]] served as \"driver expert.\" [[WTHR]] sports director and Speedway public address announcer Dave Calabro joined the crew as a pit reporter, his lone radio network appearance. This was also Gary Lee's final year on the radio network.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|[[Indianapolis Motor Speedway Radio Network|Indy Racing Radio Network]] \n|-\n!Booth Announcers!!Turn Reporters!![[Sideline reporter|Pit/garage reporters]]\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n'''[[Play-by-play|Chief Announcer]]:''' [[Bob Jenkins]]<br />\n'''Driver expert:''' [[Johnny Rutherford]]<br />\n'''[[Statistician]]:''' Howdy Bell<br />\n'''[[Historian]]:''' [[Donald Davidson (historian)|Donald Davidson]]<br />\n'''Commentary:''' [[Chris Economaki]]<br />\n|valign=\"top\"|\n'''Turn 1:''' [[Jerry Baker (announcer)|Jerry Baker]]<br />    \n'''Turn 2:''' Ken Double<br />\n'''Turn 3:''' Gary Lee<br />\n'''Turn 4:''' [[Bob Lamey]]<br />\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|Mark Jaynes (north pits)<br />Dave Calabro (center pits)<br />[[Vince Welch]] (south pits)<br />Chuck Marlowe (garages)<br />\n|}\n\n===Television===\nThe race was carried live flag-to-flag coverage in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC Sports]]. [[Paul Page]] served as host and play-by-play announcer with [[Tom Sneva]] as analyst. Longtime color commentator [[Bobby Unser]] left ABC, while [[Danny Sullivan]] was reassigned to cover [[Champ Car|CART]] races exclusively and would no longer be with the broadcast. This would be Page's final 500 for the next three years. After the 1998 season, Page would move exclusively to [[Champ Car|CART]] series broadcasts while being replaced in 1999 by soon to be former voice of the 500 Bob Jenkins.\n\nFor the first time since the early 1980s, one of the pit reporters ([[Gary Gerould]]) rode in the pace car, reporting live at the start of the race. During the broadcast itself, [[Brent Musburger]] had a small role as ''[[Wide World of Sports (U.S. TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]'' studio host.\n\nAt the track itself, the Speedway broadcast the race live on a special targeted signal, intended to be picked up by televisions sets within the radius of the grounds. This was the first and only time this special signal has been used.\n \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|[[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] [[List of Indianapolis 500 broadcasters|Television]]\n|-\n!Booth Announcers!![[Sideline reporter|Pit/garage reporters]]\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n'''Host/[[Play-by-play|Announcer]]:''' [[Paul Page]]<br />\n'''[[Color commentator|Color]]:''' [[Tom Sneva]]<br />\n|align=\"center\" valign=\"top\"|[[Jack Arute]]<br />[[Gary Gerould]]<br />[[Jerry Punch|Dr. Jerry Punch]]\n|}\n\nPractice and time trials were carried over three networks: [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]], [[ESPN]], and [[ESPN2]]. \n*Live Daily Reports (ESPN2): Paul Page, Jon Beekhuis, Jerry Punch, Jack Arute, Gary Gerould\n*Time trials ([[ESPN on ABC|ABC]]): Paul Page, Tom Sneva, Jack Arute, Gary Gerould, Brent Musberger (studio host)\n*Time trials ([[ESPN]]/[[ESPN2]]): Paul Page, Jon Beekhuis, Jerry Punch, Gary Gerould\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Commons category|1998 Indianapolis 500}}\n<gallery>\nImage:Indy500pacecar1998.JPG|1998 Chevrolet Corvette pace car\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n*''1998 Indianapolis 500 Daily Trackside Report for the Media''\n*[https